For example, I want to serve a static file with stream.

I tried `Deno.open()` like this:

```ts
serve(async () => { 
  const file = await Deno.open("./file.txt");
  return new Response(file.readable, {
    headers: { "Content-Type": "text/plain; charset=utf-8", },
  });
  // But the file cannot be closed 
  // due to the async arrow function has been returned
  file.close();
});
```

I've found an example from [Deno Blog](https://deno.com/blog/deploy-static-files):
```ts
import { serve } from "https://deno.land/std@0.120.0/http/server.ts";

const FILE_URL = new URL("/movie.webm", import.meta.url).href;

console.log("Listening on http://localhost:8000");
serve(async () => {
  const resp = await fetch(FILE_URL);
  return new Response(resp.body, {
    headers: {
      "content-type": "video/webm",
    },
  });
});
```

Besides using fetch fileURL, using [Low Level HTTP Server API](https://deno.land/manual@v1.21.1/runtime/http_server_apis_low_level) also works:

```ts
async function handle(conn: Deno.Conn) {
  const httpConn = Deno.serveHttp(conn);
  for await (const requestEvent of httpConn) {
    const file = await Deno.open("./file.txt");
    await requestEvent.respondWith(
      new Response(file.readable, {
        status: 200,
      }),
    );
    file.close();
  }
}

const server = Deno.listen({ port: 8080 });

for await (const conn of server) {
  handle(conn);
}
```

I have two questions:
1. I know the API `serve()` provides is imitating `fetch()`, so the response is **returned**. But can we have another High Level API to cover this case?

It may look like this:
```ts
unnamed_serve(async (req, res) => { 
  const file = await Deno.open("./file.txt");
  res.respondWith(new Response(file.readable, {
    headers: { "Content-Type": "text/plain; charset=utf-8", },
  }));
  file.close();
});
```

2. What's the magic that fetching a fileURL needs no closing manually?

