[We don't have a proper way to use gRPC protocol with Deno right now.](https://github.com/denoland/deno/issues/3326)

[gRPC uses HTTP2 trailer for sending `grpc-status`](https://github.com/grpc/grpc/blob/master/doc/PROTOCOL-HTTP2.md), which is [important for implementing gRPC](https://github.com/denoland/deno/issues/3326#issuecomment-819137219). However, since Deno tries to provide Web-compatible interfaces, APIs like `fetch` and `Deno.serveHttp` [do not provide any ways to read or write HTTP2 trailers](https://github.com/denoland/deno/issues/10214).

It is also undesirable to use FFI for gRPC. [Native gRPC libraries like Tonic will have to be run in executors like Tokio](https://github.com/hyperium/tonic#overview), but Deno's own Tokio event loop is not exposed. So they can't be run in tandem with Deno, as otherwise they will block Deno.

[It _is_ possible to use `Deno.connectTls` and `Deno.listenTls` to build entire HTTP2 and gRPC stack with JS.](https://github.com/prohazko2/deno-grpc) But it is hard to leverage HTTP2 implementation of Deno and would result in a performance decrease.

So I propose to add new runtime APIs for `Deno.connectGrpc` and `Deno.listenGrpc`, as follows.

```ts
declare namespace Deno {
  export function connectGrpc(
    options: ConnectGrpcOptions,
  ): Promise<GrpcChannel>;
  export interface ConnectGrpcOptions {
    // https://grpc.github.io/grpc/core/md_doc_naming.html
    host: string | URL;
    privateKey?: string;
    certChain?: string;
    caCerts?: string[];
  }
  export interface GrpcChannel extends Closer {
    call(request: GrpcRequest): GrpcResponse;
  }

  export function listenGrpc(options: ListenGrpcOptions): GrpcListener;
  export interface ListenGrpcOptions {
    addr: string;
    privateKey?: string;
    certChain?: string;
  }
  export interface GrpcListener
    extends AsyncIterableIterator<GrpcRequestEvent>, Closer {}
  export interface GrpcRequestEvent {
    readonly request: GrpcRequest;
    sendHeader(header: GrpcMetadata): Promise<void>;
    sendMessage(message: Uint8Array): Promise<void>;
    sendTrailer(trailer: GrpcMetadata): Promise<void>;
  }

  export interface GrpcRequest {
    metadata: GrpcMetadata;
    messages: AsyncGenerator<Uint8Array>;
  }
  export interface GrpcResponse {
    header: Promise<GrpcMetadata>;
    messages: AsyncGenerator<Uint8Array>;
    trailer: Promise<GrpcMetadata>;
  }
  export interface GrpcMetadata {
    [key: string]: string | Uint8Array;
  }
}
```

This is arguably a lower level API (or too high to someone. I wanted to make the interface simple). But we necessarily need this general design because [gRPC supports not only Protobuf but also other serialization formats like FlatBuffers](https://grpc.io/blog/grpc-flatbuffers/).
I would expect that [higher-level API is to be provided by codegen layers like Pbkit](https://github.com/pbkit/pbkit) as Protobuf already requires codegen anyway.

